## Comparison of Approaches

| Approach | Time Complexity | Space Complexity | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Basic Recursive** | O(2ⁿ) | O(n) call stack | Simple but slow |
| **Memoized Recursive** | O(n) | O(n) memo + stack | Fast, caches results |
| **Tail Recursive** | O(n) | O(n) call stack* | Clean, no redundancy |

> *Tail recursion **can** be O(1) space if the compiler applies **Tail Call Optimization (TCO)**, which GCC/Clang do with `-O2`.

## Key Concepts

- **Base Cases** → `fib(0) = 0`, `fib(1) = 1` stop the recursion
- **Memoization** → Stores previously computed results to avoid redundant calls
- **Tail Recursion** → Passes accumulated state forward instead of waiting for return values, enabling compiler optimization
- **Input Validation** → Throws `std::invalid_argument` for negative inputs
